Notes

  • Multi-level modeling is useful for ecology/biology due to multiple groupings.
  • Color palette function is in base R (which is nice)
  • Alpha value is two extra digits at end of HEX code!!!!!!
cols <- palette.colors(10, "Dark2")
cols.t <- paste(cols, "50", sep = "") # pro tip ... alpha is transparency and tacked onto the end of the color!
library(lme4)
  • Linear regression formula is \(Y=\alpha+\beta*X+\epsilon\), where the predicted value (Y) is the intercept (\(\alpha\)) + the estimated slope (\(\beta\)) times the X-value, plus the residual (or error; \(\epsilon\))
  • If you add up all the residuals, the distribution should be normal, and the variance is \(\sigma^{2}\).
    • SD is \(\sigma\)

Making up fake data

N <- 1000   # individual number (how many measurements have been made)
X <- rnorm(N, 4, 1) # generating the data
summary(X)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.291   3.311   3.984   3.993   4.664   7.163
plot(density(X), main = "Distribution of X")
rug(X, col = cols[1])

  • Rug plot helps visualize density of data
  • Okay, so we’re trying to figure out how X and Y are related in this kind of modeling, so here is a fake relationship we will use to calculate Y from our generated X vals
alpha <- 3
beta  <- 3
Y <- alpha + beta * X
plot(X, Y, col = cols.t[4], pch = 19, cex = 1.5, main = "Y from an equation")

  • Looked too perfect because there is no uncertainty
  • Generating data by distribution makes it easier to add variance
Y <- rnorm(N, alpha + beta * X, 0)
plot(X, Y, col = cols.t[4], pch = 19, cex = 1.5, main = "Y from a distribution")

  • Now adding sigma to add variance, performing linear regression, and plotting this line on the graph; then performing summary to see if our calculated model fits
sigma <- 10 # make sigma
Y <- rnorm(N, alpha + beta * X, sigma)
plot(X, Y, col = cols.t[4], pch = 19, cex = 1.5, main = "Y from a distribution")
lin.mod <- lm(Y ~ X) # fit the model
abline(lin.mod, col = "black", lwd = 2)

print(summary(lin.mod))

  • Note difference in significance when changing sigma/increasing uncertainty

  • As noise gets higher, it is harder to predict the relationship out of the cloud

  • We can incorporate multiple variables into this to see what exactly is affecting Y

  • Adjusted R\(^{2}\) penalizes for extra parameters, especially ones that don’t do much to explain extra variables

Multi-Level Modeling

  • Some noise can obscure the trend in data; some noise can be really valuable information that tells us more about the system

  • We’re going to edit our data so that there are groups (that may have different alphas and betas) within the population

    • Basically, we have to think of there being two levels of variance

  • Sigma group intercept is just the overall variance between the groups

J <- 10
ID <- rep(seq(J), length = N)
sigma_group_int <- 3
set.seed(15)
alpha_j <- rnorm(J, alpha, sigma_group_int)
sd(alpha_j)
## [1] 2.863328
plot(density(alpha_j), main = "Distribution of alpha_j")
rug(alpha_j, col=cols[1])

  • Since we are sampling 10 repeatedly, it’s gonna give us weird bumps/ slightly not normal distribution
Y <- rnorm(N, alpha_j[ID] + beta * X, 0)

plot(X, Y, col = cols.t[ID], pch = 19, cex = 1.5, main = "Y from a distribution")

plot(X, Y, col = cols.t[ID], pch = 19, cex = 1.5, main = "Y from a distribution")
lin.mod.group <- lm(Y ~ X)
abline(lin.mod.group, col = "black", lwd = 2)
for(j in 1:J) {

  X.1 <- subset(X, ID == j)
  Y.1 <- subset(Y, ID == j)

  lin.mod.group <- lm(Y.1 ~ X.1)
  abline(lin.mod.group, col = cols[j], lwd = 2, lty = 2)
}

  • So now we have varying intercepts!!!

  • Now going to add a sigma in and plot it

sigma <- 1
Y <- rnorm(N, alpha_j[ID] + beta * X, sigma)
plot(X, Y, col = 'gray', pch = 19, cex = 0.75, main = "Y from a distribution")
lin.mod.group <- lm(Y ~ X)
abline(lin.mod.group, col = "black", lwd = 2)

print(summary(lin.mod.group))

  • Now how do we separate the groups out and do LM for each of them plus an overall lm? LMER

  • For LMER, putting things in the parantheses means evaluate for each group. Outside parantheses is for the population

plot(X, Y, col = cols.t[ID], pch = 19, cex = 0.75, main = "Y from a distribution")
lme.mod <- lmer(Y ~ 1 + X + (1 | ID))
print(summary(lme.mod))
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: Y ~ 1 + X + (1 | ID)
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 2950.6
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4.1461 -0.6347  0.0434  0.6774  3.1522 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev.
##  ID       (Intercept) 8.115    2.849   
##  Residual             1.046    1.023   
## Number of obs: 1000, groups:  ID, 10
## 
## Fixed effects:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value
## (Intercept)  3.74267    0.91134   4.107
## X            2.95686    0.03356  88.097
## 
## Correlation of Fixed Effects:
##   (Intr)
## X -0.147
fix.ef <- as.numeric(fixef(lme.mod))

abline(a = fix.ef[1], b = fix.ef[2], col = "black", lwd = 2)
ran.ef <- as.numeric(unlist(ranef(lme.mod)))
for(j in 1:J) {
abline(a = ran.ef[j] + fix.ef[1], b = fix.ef[2], col = cols[j], lwd = 2, lty = 2)
  X.1 <- subset(X, ID == j)
  Y.1 <- subset(Y, ID == j)

  lin.mod.group <- lm(Y.1 ~ X.1)
  abline(lin.mod.group, col = cols.t[j], lwd = 2, lty = 3)

}

  • Remember to not include outliers in this analysis because the computer will apply the wrong sort of models to it (shrubs in a canopy tree analysis)
